## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Cannot forcefully kill threads |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | No abort to reset |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Obsolete, never thrown** | Dead code path |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can interrupt `finally` blocks, leave locks held, and corrupt shared data.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, honoring the timeout.
            // If the task doesn't finish in time, this throws.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call-site handling.
            throw ex.InnerException!;
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async variant — prefer this in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
// ── BEFORE (.NET Framework) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── AFTER (.NET 8) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into the work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── AFTER (async, preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** If `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion even after the timeout fires. There is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Abort()`. You must pass `CancellationToken` down into I/O calls, loops, etc:

```csharp
// ✅ Work that respects cancellation
T DoWork(CancellationToken ct)
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // check in loops
        db.Execute(query, ct);              // pass to I/O
    }
}
```

**2. Fire-and-forget risk.** If the caller times out but the delegate keeps running, you leak a `Task` doing real work (holding connections, writing files). Design work to stop promptly.

**3. `Task.Wait()` vs `await`.** The sync overload blocks a thread — fine for console apps, dangerous in ASP.NET/UI contexts (deadlock). Prefer the async variant.

**4. `WaitAsync()` (.NET 6+)** detaches the *caller* from the task but does **not** cancel the underlying work. The `CancellationTokenSource` timeout is what triggers cancellation of `work`.
